A '''palm court''' is a large [[atrium (architecture)|atrium]] with [[Arecaceae|palm trees]], usually in a prestigious hotel, where functions are staged, notably [[tea dance]]s.  Examples include the [[Langham Hotel, London|Langham Hotel]] (1865), [[Alexandra Palace]] (1873), the [[Carlton Hotel, London|Carlton Hotel]] (1899), and the [[The Ritz London Hotel|Ritz Hotel]] (1906), all in [[London]]; and the [[Palm Court (Alexandria Hotel)|Alexandria Hotel]] (court added in 1911) in [[Los Angeles, California]], and Plaza Hotel in New York city. Capitalizing on their popularity, some [[ocean liner]]s also had palm courts, notably the [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']] (1912).

The concept of the palm court orchestra, a small orchestra playing light classical music, comes from this root.

